<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><!DOCTYPE article  PUBLIC '-//OASIS//DTD DocBook XML V4.4//EN'  'http://www.docbook.org/xml/4.4/docbookx.dtd'><article><articleinfo><title>EliezerCroitoru/Drafts/HttpKnocker</title><revhistory><revision><revnumber>2</revnumber><date>2015-02-24 01:35:34</date><authorinitials>Eliezer Croitoru</authorinitials><revremark>Fixing a typo</revremark></revision><revision><revnumber>1</revnumber><date>2015-02-24 01:11:30</date><authorinitials>Eliezer Croitoru</authorinitials></revision></revhistory></articleinfo><para>I am writing down the idea to make it public visible. </para><section><title>HTTP Knocking</title><para>Similar to port knocking there is a way to implement a squid helper which will provide an API to a HTTP helper that will somehow be connected to some changing hashing\coding system and will &quot;open doors&quot; if needed. </para></section><section><title>Honey Pot</title><para>Almost like the above idea squid can be used as a honey pot and will trigger a block based on many of the request parts. </para></section></article>